Laws,Â regulationsÂ andÂ policiesÂ canÂ alsoÂ help:Â LawsÂ limitingÂ theÂ financialÂ incentivesÂ thatÂ enableÂ pranksters,Â propagandists,Â andÂ advertisersÂ inÂ producingÂ misinformationÂ toÂ drawÂ ourÂ attentionÂ andÂ clicks.Â RegulationsÂ thatÂ restrictÂ theÂ collectionÂ andÂ exchangeÂ ofÂ personalÂ information,Â suchÂ asÂ theÂ recentÂ EuropeanÂ GDPR.Â EthicalÂ 2policiesÂ thatÂ protectÂ ourÂ limitedÂ attentionÂ capitalÂ soÂ thatÂ weÂ doÂ notÂ sinkÂ inÂ theÂ constantÂ waveÂ ofÂ informationÂ thatÂ reachesÂ usÂ everyÂ day.Â Â Policies,Â laws,Â regulations,Â trustedÂ authorities,Â andÂ technologyÂ willÂ help,Â butÂ theyÂ willÂ notÂ solveÂ theÂ problemÂ ofÂ propaganda,Â misinformation,Â andÂ "fakeÂ news"Â ifÂ weÂ justÂ relyÂ onÂ them.Â NoÂ solutionÂ willÂ beÂ completeÂ withoutÂ activeÂ engagementÂ ofÂ theÂ citizen,Â epistemologicalÂ educationÂ (notÂ justÂ mediaÂ literacyÂ [23]),Â andÂ anÂ activeÂ democraticÂ society.Â WeÂ needÂ toÂ beÂ awareÂ ofÂ whyÂ weÂ believeÂ whatÂ weÂ believeÂ andÂ ofÂ ourÂ ownÂ biases.Â WeÂ needÂ toÂ listenÂ toÂ thoseÂ outsideÂ ourÂ echoÂ chambers.Â AndÂ weÂ needÂ toÂ applyÂ criticalÂ thinkingÂ habituallyÂ soÂ thatÂ weÂ enjoyÂ practicingÂ itÂ onÂ aÂ dailyÂ basis.Â IfÂ weÂ adoptÂ aÂ solutionÂ thatÂ requiresÂ evenÂ lessÂ useÂ ofÂ ourÂ brain,Â weÂ mayÂ justÂ becomeÂ irrelevantÂ [24].Â Â TheÂ aboveÂ isÂ aÂ longÂ listÂ ofÂ challengingÂ skills.Â MasteryÂ ofÂ (mostÂ of)Â theseÂ skillsÂ isÂ necessaryÂ forÂ aÂ successfulÂ lifeÂ inÂ theÂ 21stÂ centuryÂ andÂ beyond.Â ItÂ isÂ notÂ easyÂ becauseÂ weÂ needÂ toÂ changeÂ ourselves.Â ButÂ that'sÂ whatÂ EducationÂ wasÂ alwaysÂ about.Â Â Â Â Â Â ReferencesÂ [1]Â Â "SeparatingÂ TruthÂ fromÂ Lies"Â (emailÂ interview),Â byÂ AlisonÂ HeadÂ andÂ KirstenÂ Hostetler,Â ProjectÂ InformationÂ Literacy,Â SmartÂ TalkÂ Interview,Â no.Â 27Â (21Â FebruaryÂ 2017)Â http://www.projectinfolit.org/takisÂ­metaxasÂ­smartÂ­talk.htmlÂ Â [2]Â Â HarryÂ Frankfurt,Â "OnÂ Bullshit."Â Princeton,Â NJ:Â PrincetonÂ UniversityÂ Press,Â 2005.Â Â [3 These smart contracts allow Ethereum Private Sidechains to be estab- lished on-demand, in a similar way to how a user of a web browser can establish a secure connection to a web server by simply entering in a URL such as https://example.com/.

This system of bootstrapping information for blockchain is analogous to the Domain Name System (DNS), Public Key Infrastructure (PKI), and Transport Layer Security (TLS) which combine to allow users of web browsers to enter a URL, for example https://example.com/ , and be able to instantly, securely view information from a remote web server.

From the altmetrics  community, an initiative was taken to develop standards for altmetric indicators and use  in the  context of the US National Information Standards Organization (NISO) as a result of a breakout  session at the altmetrics12  conference  (http://altmetrics.org/altmetrics12 ) (National  Information Standards Organization, 2016) .
For instance, the  readership counts provided by Mendeley  (http://www.mendeley.com ) include total  number of users who have saved (added) a document to their private libraries.

Other tools such as BibSonomy   ( https://www.bibsonomy.org/ ), Zotero  (https://www.zotero.org ), and CiteULike   (http://www.citeulike.org/ ) also offer information on the posted counts/us ers, tags, posting  history and userâ€™s info plus the bibliographic information of the bookmarked or saved documents , although their APIs are not yet fully developed  (Haustein, 2016) .

Other academic platforms include Publons   (https: //publons.com/home/ ), which has recently been acquired by Clarivate Analyitics or  PubPeer  (https://pubpeer.com/ ), which offer post publication peer comments and scores  for scholarly biomedical or multidisciplinary publi cations.
A more general  platform  is  Reddit  (https://www.reddit.com/dev/api ), which provide s information such as comments  and votes  to the posts provided by its users.

A  common metric  available through these sources include s mentions of scholarly object s.
